comments.body:
I thought this was intended to be `TextNode`, but `findDOMNode` on a component that only returns a string actually produces an object that just holds a reference to the Fiber instance.

```js
ReactDOM.render(
  React.createElement(class extends React.Component {
    componentDidMount () {
      console.log(ReactDOM.findDOMNode(this))
    }
    render () {
      return 'test'
    }
  }),
  document.body.appendChild(document.createElement('div'))
)
```

<img width="426" alt="image" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/73085/38530601-5ad3d96c-3ca6-11e8-8dbd-b545300aa068.png">

---

This would actually mean that the correct return type should be `{} | null`, but that would be awfully annoying to use in the common case of a component that mounts a DOM element.

